[2] Cholera, school children - Malaysia (Semporna)
Date: Thu, 12 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Malaysia Star [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2005/5/12/nation/10925752&sec=nation>

Over 100 pupils and a cook hospitalized for cholera
---------------------------------------------------
More than 100 pupils and a canteen cook in the Semporna district have been
admitted to the hospital after they showed signs of suffering from cholera.
Semporna Hospital authorities said they can cope with the high number of
admissions but urged the public to practice better hygiene. Residents in
the district have been advised to drink boiled water and eat home-cooked food.
The cholera outbreak was first detected on Fri, 6 May 2005 when a cook at
the SK Bubul II, who was suffering from fever, diarrhea, and vomiting was
rushed to the hospital. Since then, 106 pupils from the school and 7
students from the nearby SMK Kabongan II, had also be admitted. Health
authorities in the district have ordered the canteens in the 2 schools to
close.
The district office and the health office have sent a notice to all
residents in the Semporna district to observe cleanliness at home and
elsewhere to prevent cholera from spreading to more schools and kampungs.
Semporna assistant district officer Bianos Kuntong told The Star that the
health department confirmed the cholera outbreak in a report to their
office on Tue, 10 May 2005. They were now taking preventive measures
through public education.
Sabah Health Department deputy director Dr Yusof Ibrahim said a health team
from Tawau was sent to Semporna yesterday to help local health officials
investigate the cause as well as to help in the preventive measures.
Semporna hospital director Dr Norazam Kamaruzaman said they have admitted
the carriers and also those who were in contact with them, as part of an
effort to isolate them from further interaction with other people.
"We are taking rectal swabs and those who show no signs of infection after
3 checks will be discharged," he said, adding that though cholera was
endemic to Semporna the current outbreak was higher then the previous outbreak.
[With an infected food worker, this may well be a point-source outbreak.
The posting does not state whether the cook worked at both schools - Mod.LL]
