[3] Cholera - Cameroon (Western Provinces)
Date: Mon, 9 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail
Source: IRIN News [edited]
<http://www.irinnews.org/report.asp?ReportID=47020&SelectRegion=West_Africa&SelectCountry=CAMEROON>

Cholera outbreak on wane after 42 deaths
----------------------------------------
A cholera outbreak which has killed at least 42 people and infected almost
1400 since the beginning of 2005 in western Cameroon despite government
measures to contain the disease is finally receding, health officials told
IRIN on Mon 9 May 2005.
In the worst-hit area for example, in the coastal Littoral province, where
29 people have died and 1141 were infected, fatalities were sharply down in
May 2005, said Antoine Mouangue, who heads the province's hospital services.
"We are now in an endemic phase, having registered 3 to 11 cholera cases
per week over the last weeks," he said in a telephone interview from
Douala, the country's economic capital. "Previously, we had registered up
to 80 new cases a week," he said, referring to Littoral province during the
period between 27 Dec 2004 and 8 Mar 2005.
In the city of Douala, where there were more than 500 cases of cholera but
good medical facilities, there were only 3 deaths. Also badly affected by
the outbreak were 2 Cameroonian provinces bordering Nigeria, West province
and South-West province.
West province had registered 131 cases of cholera and 8 deaths since 28 Mar
2005, but no new cases had been detected in the last 4 days, the province's
public health delegate Hammadou Fopa told IRIN on Mon, 9 May 2005.
In South-West province 5 of the 85 people infected have died, the
province's public health delegate Martin Mafany told IRIN. But no new cases
had been recorded over the last 2 weeks.
Cholera is endemic in Cameroon, where it breaks out every year from
December through June if not properly tackled. In 2004 at least 6400 people
were infected nationwide and more than 130 people died of cholera across
the country, according to government figures. A majority of the victims
were found in the West and Littoral provinces.
